Linux - like Apple OS and Windows OS, popular in open source community

redhat — large corporate costumers and support
ubuntu — ease of use on servers, desktops, and laptops
mint — desktop users with proprietary media support
coreos — clustered, containerized deployment of apps

Some places to start your research:

https://distrowatch.com/
— Distro Watch has been around since 2001 as a source of news about Linux distributions and other Free and Open-Source operating systems.

https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Comparison_of_Linux_distributions
— Wikipedia article comparing current and former Linux distributions.

Vagrant
Type vagrant init ubuntu/trusty64 to tell Vagrant what kind of Linux virtual machine you would like to run.
Type vagrant up to download and start running the virtual machine

vagrant status — shows current status of virtual machine
vagrant suspend — for saving and taking a break
vagrant ssh — to connect and log into the virtual machine
vagrant halt — more like shutting down, frees up ram, but slower than vagrant halt
vagrant destroy — delete function

going to cd /
when you ls -al, you see a bunch of files here
the etc file is important for modifying web and database servers
the var file is for variable files you expect to change in size over time
the bin file is where executable binaries are stored, accessible by all users, for running applications (e.g. - the ls command)
sbin file is the same as bin, but only used by root user for system administration
lib file is for libraries that support the bin filterItems
usr is for user programs, difference between this and /bin is that this isn't used for boot up and sys maintenance processes

echo $PATH to check all the shortcuts available
for configuring your own $path: https://askubuntu.com/questions/60218/how-to-add-a-directory-to-the-path
